# 1. Product class changes
In the updated version, the Product class was modified to include a new field called Category. This allows products to be grouped into categories such as Electronics and Accessories, which improves organization and makes filtering easier in the program.

The product display method was also updated. Before, it only showed the Id, Name, Price, and Stock. Now it displays:

- Id, Name, Category, Price, and Remaining Stock.

This makes the product information more complete and user-friendly.
At the same time, several helper methods were removed from the class:

- HasEnoughStock(int)

- GetItemTotal(int)

- DeductStock(int)

These methods were originally responsible for handling stock checking and calculation. In the new version, their logic was moved outside the class and handled directly in the main program and methods.

This means the Product class is now simpler, but it also shifts more responsibility to the main program instead of keeping behavior inside the object.


# 2. New Order system
A completely new class called Order was introduced in the second version. This class contains:

- ReceiptNumber

- FinalTotal

- Date

This is a major addition because it allows the system to store completed transactions.

Unlike the first version, which only prints a receipt once and forgets it, the new version now supports order history tracking. This means past purchases can be reviewed later, making the program more realistic and closer to an actual shopping system.


# 3. Program structure upgrade (big improvement)
The structure of the program was heavily improved in the second version.

Before, the program only had a single loop inside Main that handled everything:

- displaying products

- selecting items

- adding to cart

- checkout

- receipt generation

In the new version, the program is now menu-driven. The user can choose from multiple options:

- View Products

- Search Product

- Filter by Category

- Manage Cart

- View Order History

- Exit

This makes the program more organized and easier to navigate. It also separates different features instead of putting everything in one loop, which improves readability and structure.

# 4. Cart system improvement

The cart system was significantly improved in the second version.

Before, the cart was only managed inside Main using arrays, and once an item was added, there was no proper way to modify it except continuing the loop.

In the updated version, the cart is now handled using dedicated methods:

- AddToCart()

- CartMenu()

The CartMenu system adds several new features:

- View cart items

- Remove specific items

- Update item quantity

- Clear the entire cart

- Proceed to checkout


This is a major improvement because the cart is now interactive and flexible, similar to real online shopping systems.


# 5. Checkout system improvements

The checkout process in the second version is much more complete compared to the first.

Before, checkout simply:

- calculated totals

- applied discount if applicable

- printed a receipt


In the new version, checkout now includes:

- Receipt number generation

- Date and time stamping using DateTime.Now

- Payment input from the user

- Validation to ensure sufficient payment

- Change calculation

- Discount application (10% if total is 5000 or more)

- Saving the transaction into order history


This makes the checkout process more realistic and complete, as it now simulates an actual purchase flow.


# 6. Stock handling improvements

Stock management was also improved in the second version.

Before:

Stock was only reduced when items were added to the cart

After:

Stock is reduced when items are added
Stock is restored when items are removed from the cart
Stock is restored when the cart is cleared
Stock is properly adjusted when updating item quantities

This makes inventory handling more accurate and prevents inconsistencies between the cart and actual product stock.


# 7. New features added

The second version introduces several new features that were not present in the first version:

- Product search by name using string matching

- Filtering products by category (Electronics / Accessories)

- Order history display using a list of Order objects

- Low stock warning when stock reaches 5 or below

- Improved input validation using TryParse in multiple areas


These additions make the system more interactive and closer to a real shopping application.


 # 8. Code organization improvement

One of the biggest improvements in the second version is how the code is organized.

Before, everything was written directly inside the Main method, which made the program harder to read and maintain.

In the updated version, the logic is split into separate methods:

- AddToCart

- CartMenu

- Checkout


This makes the code more modular, easier to debug, and easier to expand in the future. It also improves readability since each function now has a specific responsibility instead of mixing all logic together.

# Overall summary

Overall, the second version is a major improvement over the first version. It introduces better structure, additional features, and more realistic system behavior.

The program now behaves more like a real shopping system with proper cart management, order history, and improved user interaction. However, there is still room for improvement in object-oriented design, especially in keeping more logic inside classes instead of the main program.
